<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="user-story-mapping">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>product</group>
    <domain>product-planning</domain>
    <summary>Arrange stories in 2D: activities (left-to-right = journey) and tasks (top-to-bottom = priority). Walking skeleton is one task per activity, end-to-end. Release slices span full backbone.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>story-mapping</tag>
      <tag>user-journey</tag>
      <tag>release-planning</tag>
      <tag>backbone</tag>
      <tag>skeleton</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>User Story Mapping</title>

    <summary>User story mapping arranges stories into a two-dimensional model: user activities as the horizontal backbone (left-to-right = user journey) and tasks stacked vertically by priority within each activity. The walking skeleton is exactly one task per activity, forming an end-to-end working flow that becomes the earliest shippable version. Release slices are horizontal cuts that span the full backbone. Flat backlogs lose the context of user workflows: stories get prioritized in isolation without seeing whether the full journey is covered. A story map makes missing steps visible, prevents releases that cover only one column of the journey, and creates a shared picture for cross-functional teams before sprint planning.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Flat backlogs lose the context of user workflows: stories get prioritized in isolation without seeing whether the full journey is covered. A story map makes missing steps visible, prevents releases that cover only one column of the journey, and creates a shared picture for cross-functional teams before sprint planning.</p>
      <p>A backbone subagent emits the high-level user activities (5–10 verbs) given a persona and journey scope. A task-decomposer subagent produces per-activity tasks with priority rank within column. A skeleton subagent picks the minimal task per activity to make an end-to-end working flow. A release-slicer subagent partitions remaining tasks into release rows aligned to the roadmap. A reviewer subagent checks: every activity has a task, walking skeleton is end-to-end, no release is empty, no task is orphaned.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Designing an end-to-end user journey across multiple activities.</item>
        <item>Slicing a backlog into shippable releases when a flat list lost journey context.</item>
        <item>Cross-functional alignment before sprint planning (engineering, design, PM need a shared picture).</item>
        <item>Identifying the walking skeleton for an MVP — pairs with mvp-scoping.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Pure technical work (infrastructure, refactors, platform changes) — no user-facing backbone exists.</item>
        <item>Tiny single-flow features — direct user stories with acceptance criteria suffice.</item>
        <item>Teams without shared journey understanding yet — do user-journey-mapping or JTBD interviews first.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="backbone">
      <rule>
        <statement>The backbone is a left-to-right sequence of 5–10 verb-phrase user activities that represent the user's journey. Use verb phrases ("Create Project"), never nouns ("Project").</statement>
        <rationale>Nouns hide the action and make it impossible to see whether the user can actually accomplish anything. Verb phrases make activities testable: you can verify whether a user can "Create Project."</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="tasks">
      <rule>
        <statement>Under each backbone activity, list specific user tasks ordered vertically by importance (higher = more important). Cap at 6 tasks per column.</statement>
        <rationale>Vertical ordering is the priority signal. More than 6 tasks per column makes the map unreadable and usually means the backbone activity needs to be split.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Include at least one error path or empty-state task per activity — not just the happy path.</statement>
        <rationale>Happy-path-only maps produce releases that break on the first edge case. Error paths are where users abandon products.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="walking-skeleton">
      <rule>
        <statement>The walking skeleton is exactly one task per backbone activity — the minimum set that forms an end-to-end working flow. Every backbone activity must have exactly one skeleton task; the flow must be completeable end-to-end.</statement>
        <rationale>Without the walking skeleton constraint, Release 1 becomes a maximalist feature dump. The skeleton forces the team to ask "what is the thinnest possible flow that works?"</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="release-slices">
      <rule>
        <statement>Each release slice is a horizontal cut that spans the full backbone. A release that covers only 2 of 5 activities means users cannot complete the journey.</statement>
        <rationale>Partial-backbone releases ship an incomplete experience. Users who reach the edge of the covered activities are blocked and churn. Every slice must be shippable value — something a user can accomplish end-to-end.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="5-step-mapping-process">
      <rule>
        <statement>Step 1 — Frame the Journey: Before writing any activities, define who is the user, what is their big goal, and where does the journey start and end.</statement>
        <rationale>Without a journey frame the backbone drifts into product-internal activities instead of user-facing ones.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Step 2 — Build the Backbone: Write activities as verb phrases on cards, arrange left-to-right in journey order, then verify the sequence by reading it aloud as a user narrative.</statement>
        <rationale>The read-aloud test catches activities in the wrong order and reveals missing steps before you add tasks.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Step 3 — Add Tasks: For each activity, list what the user does there, place tasks in the activity column, arrange vertically by importance (top = most important). Do not write tasks before the backbone is complete.</statement>
        <rationale>Writing tasks before the backbone produces task lists, not a story map. The backbone provides the grouping context that gives vertical ordering its meaning.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Step 4 — Identify the Walking Skeleton: Draw a line separating the walking skeleton (one task per activity, end-to-end flow) from all remaining tasks. The skeleton must not skip any backbone activity.</statement>
        <rationale>Skipping an activity in the skeleton means the user cannot complete the end-to-end journey — the skeleton is broken by definition.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Step 5 — Slice Releases: For each release, define the value it delivers, draw a horizontal line, name the release goal, and verify the slice spans all backbone activities.</statement>
        <rationale>Naming the release goal forces the team to ask "what can a user do after this release that they could not do before?" If the answer is unclear, the slice is not ready.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Do not run backbone, task, and release-slicing in one pass. Run as three sequential steps; quality drops sharply when combined.</statement>
        <rationale>Each step requires a different thinking mode. Combined passes produce noise-rich maps with undisciplined priority ordering.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="ecommerce-example">
      <example type="good" title="E-commerce Story Map">
        <note>5-activity backbone. Walking skeleton = minimal end-to-end purchase. Release 1 adds filters and cart management. Release 2 adds advanced features.</note>
        <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[
Backbone: Browse Products → View Product → Add to Cart → Checkout → Receive Order

Walking Skeleton:
| Browse        | View         | Cart       | Checkout        | Receive             |
|---------------|--------------|------------|-----------------|---------------------|
| See list      | See details  | Add item   | Enter payment   | Get confirmation    |

Release 1 (MVP):
| Browse           | View         | Cart            | Checkout         | Receive      |
|------------------|--------------|-----------------|------------------|--------------|
| Filter category  | See images   | Update quantity | Enter shipping   | Email receipt|
| Basic search     | See price    | Remove item     | Choose method    |              |

Release 2 (Enhanced):
| Browse           | View         | Cart            | Checkout    | Receive        |
|------------------|--------------|-----------------|-------------|----------------|
| Advanced filters | Reviews      | Save for later  | Apple Pay   | Track shipment |
| Sort options     | Size guide   | Recommendations | Guest check |                |
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="project-management-example">
      <example type="good" title="Project Management Story Map">
        <note>4-activity backbone. Each release slice spans all 4 activities.</note>
        <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[
Backbone: Create Project → Add Tasks → Track Progress → Complete Project

Walking Skeleton:
| Create       | Add Tasks    | Track          | Complete  |
|--------------|--------------|----------------|-----------|
| Name project | Add task     | See task status| Mark done |

Release 1 (Core):
| Create      | Add Tasks  | Track         | Complete        |
|-------------|------------|---------------|-----------------|
| Description | Due dates  | Kanban board  | Archive project |
| Invite      | Assign     | Basic filters |                 |
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Backbone activities written as nouns ("Dashboard", "Reports") instead of verb phrases ("View Dashboard", "Generate Report").</description>
        <reason>Nouns hide the user action and make priority ordering arbitrary. Verb phrases are testable: you can verify whether a user can accomplish the activity.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Walking skeleton skips one or more backbone activities.</description>
        <reason>A skeleton with gaps means the user cannot complete the end-to-end journey. Releases built on a broken skeleton ship an incomplete experience by design.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Release slice covers only 1–2 activities out of the full backbone.</description>
        <reason>Users hit a wall at the edge of the covered activities and cannot complete their goal. Every release must span the full backbone — even if each column gets only one task in that release.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Map built once at project start and never updated.</description>
        <reason>A static map loses fidelity within one sprint cycle as scope changes. Treat it as a living artifact tied to quarterly roadmap reviews.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Only happy-path tasks in each activity column.</description>
        <reason>Error paths, empty states, and failure recovery are where users abandon products. Missing them from the map means they are never prioritized into a release.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Build the backbone first with verbs in user-journey order; then add tasks. Reverse order produces noise.</statement>
        <rationale>Backbone-first approach ensures the context exists for meaningful task prioritization.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Walking skeleton is non-negotiable: exactly one task per backbone activity and end-to-end working flow.</statement>
        <rationale>The skeleton is the minimum viable release contract; without it, Release 1 becomes a feature soup.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Each release slice must span the full backbone, not just one column. Otherwise users can't complete the journey.</statement>
        <rationale>Partial-backbone releases are broken by definition.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Include error/edge tasks in the columns, not just happy path.</statement>
        <rationale>Error handling determines user retention; happy path alone is incomplete.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Update the map at every quarterly review; treat it as living, not a deliverable.</statement>
        <rationale>Maps drift; periodic sync with roadmap reality keeps them useful.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Pair the map with the spec: each release-bound task gets a story-card with acceptance criteria.</statement>
        <rationale>Maps are a planning tool; acceptance criteria drive implementation and testing.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>For solo dev work, drop the workshop ceremony but keep the structure: backbone + skeleton + 2 release slices.</statement>
        <rationale>Structure applies even without cross-functional teams; it forces clarity on priority and scope.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <p>LLMs collapse activities into nouns ("Dashboard") instead of verbs ("View Dashboard"). Force verb-phrase format in the schema.</p>

      <p>Without a walking-skeleton constraint, agents produce a maximalist Release 1. Enforce "one task per column for skeleton" in the schema.</p>

      <p>Agents tend to omit error / empty-state / failure tasks. Add a "include 1+ error path per activity" rule.</p>

      <p>Story maps are 2D; ASCII rendering is fragile. Keep authoritative source as JSON, render markdown tables per release for human readers.</p>

      <p>Human-in-loop checkpoints: (a) backbone approval, (b) walking-skeleton selection, (c) release-slice lock-in.</p>

      <p>Don't let the same agent produce backbone + tasks + slices in one shot — quality drops sharply. Run as a 3-stage pipeline.</p>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/story-map.md" purpose="Tabular story map with backbone, skeleton, release rows, and parking lot."/>
      <template path="templates/story-card.md" purpose="Per-task story card with placement, user story, acceptance criteria, and estimate."/>
    </templates>

    <see-also>
      <link href="https://www.jpattonassociates.com/the-new-backlog/"/>
      <link href="https://www.aha.io/roadmapping/guide/templates/user-story-map"/>
